Three main technologies are being utilised in carbon capture: pre-combustion, post-combustion and oxyfuel combustion routes. Here, the first two routes represent 96.6% of the literature work until 2018, while oxy-reforming technology showed only 3.4% of the total publications (Omoregbe et al. 2020). The utilisation of liquid solvents in pre- and post-combustion technologies is usually done in an absorber packed-bed in a counter-current directions, where the fuel gas (pre-combustion) or the exhausted flue gas (post-combustion) is pumped from the bottom of the reactor to the top, while simultaneously, the flow of the chemical or physical solvent flows from top to bottom. Temperature or a pressure swing is then applied to release the majority of absorbed CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
