Globally, there are 22 demo projects for carbon capture and storage based on power generation with the majority share of pre- and post-combustion projects, nearly equalling 10 and 9, respectively. There are only three demo projects based on oxyfuel combustion projects (Vega et al. 2020). In terms of countries that invest in carbon capture and storage, the USA is leading the world with seven projects, and China comes second with five demo projects. For carbon capture technologies to become economic feasible, having adequate carbon pricing is crucial either in carbon tax or carbon allowances. By 2019, carbon tax significantly varied from one country to another, with values ranging from a few dollars to one hundred $/tonne of CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
