				\begin{document}$$\hbox {CO}_{2}$$\end{document} is captured from flue gases, transported, compressed and finally injected in supercritical or liquefied form into suitable subsurface formations, either in a saline aquifer (Bradshaw et al. 2007; Michael et al. 2010) or, potentially, used for enhanced oil recovery (Godec et al. 2013). Ideally, the storage formation, which needs to be at a depth greater than 1 km to ensure that CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {CO}_{2}$$\end{document} remains in the supercritical phase, is characterised by numerous intercalations of tight aquitrade rocks, e.g. shales, within the reservoir rock units, e.g. sandstone or carbonate. Such multiple confinements ensure the retention security necessary to impede the upward migration and leakage of the injected CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
