sec.p:
Biochar is a product (solid form) resulted from biomass pyrolysis in the absence of oxygen content (oxygen-free atmosphere) (Dhyani and Bhaskar 2018; Balajii and Niju 2019). It is beneficial as an energy supplier because of its remarkable merits (i.e. high energy density) (Weber and Quicker 2018). Besides, it has been used in different applications (i.e. wastewater treatment and soil amendment). The physicochemical characters of the produced char differ depending on the operational pyrolysis parameters (i.e. feedstock, heating rate and residence time) (Cha et al. 2016). Physiochemical features of biochar (i.e. surface area, porosity and constituent functional groups) were optimised in CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
